Part I - Possible impact of sociodemographic characteristics on performance of students¶

by Mbang Ernest Ngong¶

Introduction¶

The PISA dataset is part of the OECD's Programme for International Student Assessment. OECD is short for 'Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development'. It is a unique forum comprised of the governments of 37 democracies where market-based economies collaborate to develop policy standards so as to promote sustainable economic growth across these countries.

The PISA survey is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. Its main aim is to examine how well students have learned the school curriculum and how well they are prepared for life beyond school.

This danalysis focuses on data collected for the PISA survey of 2012. In this survey, approximately 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the assessment of reading, mathematics and science. This data represents about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.
The PISA 2012 dataset is a huge dataset comprising approximately 635 variables however, we shall narrow it down to few variables of interest for this analysis.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original PISA dataset had approximately 636 rows and approximately 500,000 rows but our dataset of interest has 18 columns and same number of rows(485,490)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My singled out dataset consist of sociodemographic characteristics associated with students and variables that assess characteristics such as their reading strength, maths ability. I shall be interested in the association between their abilities and sociodemographic factors like country of participant, Gender etc.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Variables like the student weight score which determines the overall strength of students across categories shall be imperative in determining if a student is estimated to be successful or not. Math experience,reading strength as well as their attitudes shall be compared to characteristics like their Gender, as well as other sociodemographic variables.

In [93]:
# Top 5 countries summary
summary_p=dfi_psi.Country.value_counts(normalize=True)*100
summary_p=summary_p.head(5)

# Method that plots a bar chart given a summary of the data
def sumbar(summary_p,title,xlabel,ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=[12,5])
    ind=summary_p.index
    vl=summary_p.values
    sb.barplot(x=ind,y=vl,color=sb.color_palette()[0])
    plt.title(title,fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel,fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=14)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=14)

# plotting bar given title and axis values
title='Top 5 Countries with most participation in the PISA 2012 survey'
sumbar(summary_p,title,'Country Name','Percentage')

Observation
From the pie chart above, it can be seen that the top 5 countries that participated in the PISA 2012 survey were Mexico, Italy, Spain, Canada and Brazil. Brasil toped the list at close to 7%. It is noticeable that the percentages of the top 5 countries are small. This is because there are a wide category of countries (68) and percentages cshare across all of them.

# Method below plots a pie charts
def sumpie(oecd_counts,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=[12,5])
    plt.pie(oecd_counts, labels = oecd_counts.index, startangle = 90,
        counterclock = False);
    plt.title(title,fontsize=14)
    plt.axis('square')

# method to plot a histogram given the variable and bin step
def hisp(var,title,bins):
  # data setup for histogram
    bins = np.arange(0, dfi_psi[var].max()+bins, bins)
    plt.hist(data=dfi_psi,x=var, bins = bins)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(var)

#plotting a histogram chart of participants reading strenght using the hisp method 

title='Reading stregth distribution of participants'
# Plotting bars with different bin sizes using subplots
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 5])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1) 
hisp('Reading strength',title,5)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2) 
hisp('Reading strength',title,30)

Observation
From the chart above, it can be seen that both graphs show a relatively normal distribution implying there is a normal distrubution of reading strength across all participating countries.

Question 7
What is the distribution of PISA participant's Weighted student score?
Visualisation :

In [99]:
# log transfomed and scaled histogram plotting method
def histransformed(var,title):
  # data setup for histogram
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(-1, 3+0.1, 0.1)
    plt.hist(data=dfi_psi,x=var, bins = bins)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.xscale('log')
    ticks = [0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100, 300, 1000]
    labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
    plt.xticks(ticks,labels)

#plotting a histogram chart of participants reading strenght using the hisp and histransformed method 

title='Weighted student score distribution of participants'
# Plotting bars with different bin sizes using subplots
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 5])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1) 
hisp('Weighted student score',title,20)
#plotting transformed subplot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2) 
histransformed('Weighted student score','Log transformed Weighted student score distribution of participants')

Observation
From the chart above, it is observed that the data seemed skewed to the right with seeemingly poor construction of the chart with many outliers. The log transformation addressed this issue and a bimodal nature was observed as well as right skewedness.

    vl=summary_p.values
    sb.barplot(x=ind,y=vl,color=sb.color_palette()[0],order=order)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Majority of our variables of interest were normal and ordinal variables and they often showed farely predictable patherns in the distribution of their categories. We visualised two continuous variables that sought to communicate the reading strenth of participants and their weighted score. The normal distribution was observed in the variable that looked at students reading strengths while a right skewed graph was observed on the weightedscore of studenstacross categories. For the weighted score, a log transformation and scaling was done in other to generate a farely legible and more appreciable graph.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

On the weighted student score, a right skewed observation was seen and the graph had to be transformed in other for a more representable observation to be seen. # method to plot correlation between two variable while computing their Correlatio coefficient along
def corrp(x,y,xlabel,ylabel):
    ccoefficient=dfi_psi[x].corr(dfi_psi[y])
    print('Correlation coefficient',ccoefficient.round(2))
    sb.regplot(data = dfi_psi, x = x, y = y, x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':1/10}, fit_reg=False)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title('Correlation between Student reading strenght and their weighted score');

# passing plot parameters and plotting chart
x='Weighted student score'
y='Reading strength'
corrp(x,y,'Weighted student score','Student reading strength')

Correlation coefficient -0.04

Observation
From the graph above, it can be seen that there is no correlation between a students reading strength and their predictive success score.

Conclusions¶

This dataset was made up of more than 600 columns and approximately 500,000 rows. It was succesfully loaded and sliced for variables of interest. The data was explored and the only cleaning conducted on it was that of dropping dupicates. Pandas was allowed to handle null values by default. Univariate, bivariate and multivariate visuals were run as obseved. Categoricals variables( both norminbal and ordinal) were accessed and farely predictable patherns were observed in analysis. Our main continuous variables of interest were student reading ability which was forund to have a farely normal distribution in contrast to weighted score of students which was found to have a rather skewed distribution. The skewed nature of this weighted student score could be felt especially at the bivariate and multivariate analysis as it was integral in most of the analysis and highlighted the dominance of OECd countries in the study perhaps highlighting their relevance.
